          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During a surgical procedure, a patient's hypoglossal nerve is inadvertently damaged. Which action of the tongue would remain intact despite this injury?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Protrusion of the tongue</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Protrusion is performed by genioglossus, which is supplied by the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) and would be paralysed.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Retraction and depression of the tongue</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Hyoglossus retracts and depresses the tongue and is supplied by CN XII, so this action would be lost.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Elevation of the posterior tongue to close the oropharyngeal isthmus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Palatoglossus elevates the posterior tongue and is the sole tongue muscle NOT supplied by CN XII — it receives its innervation from the vagus nerve (CN X) via the pharyngeal plexus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Curling the tip of the tongue upward</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Curling the tip requires the superior longitudinal muscle, an intrinsic muscle supplied by CN XII.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember: all tongue muscles are supplied by CN XII except palatoglossus, which receives innervation from the vagus nerve (CN X) via the pharyngeal plexus."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Palatoglossus is the one exception to the rule that all tongue muscles are supplied by the hypoglossal nerve."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
