          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with a right-sided hypoglossal nerve injury is asked to protrude the t</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a right-sided hypoglossal nerve injury is asked to protrude the tongue. In which direction does it deviate, and why?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>To the left, because the intact right genioglossus pushes the tongue across the midline</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. If the right CN XII is damaged, the right genioglossus is paralysed and cannot exert any protrusive force.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>To the right, because the unopposed left genioglossus pushes its half forward while the paralysed right side lags</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Each genioglossus protrudes its own half of the tongue. When the right CN XII is injured, only the left genioglossus pushes forward, so the tongue tip deviates toward the paralysed (right) side.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>To the left, because the damaged nerve causes spasm of the right styloglossus pulling the tongue leftward</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. A lower motor neuron lesion causes flaccid paralysis and wasting, not spasm. Styloglossus retracts the tongue but does not cause contralateral deviation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>No deviation, because both genioglossus muscles share a midline raphe and act as a single unit</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The two genioglossus muscles act independently. Unilateral CN XII palsy produces clear ipsilateral deviation, often accompanied by visible wasting of the affected hemitongue.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "In CN XII palsy the tongue deviates toward the affected side because the intact genioglossus on the healthy side pushes forward unopposed while the paralysed side cannot contribute."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. In peripheral CN XII palsy the tongue always deviates toward the side of the lesion on protrusion."
                }
              ],
